# Styling System Contract

This file defines the visual language of the application, how Tailwind CSS is used, and how shadcn/ui must be integrated.
It combines the design tokens, Tailwind, and shadcn rules into a single source of truth.

---

# 1. Token Architecture (Tailwind v4 model)

Design tokens are defined at the CSS level using Tailwind v4 `@theme`.
- Tokens are the single source of truth for the visual language.
- Tailwind utilities are consumers of tokens.
- shadcn/ui components consume semantic tokens only.
- Features are NOT allowed to define styling systems or visual rules.

## 1.1 Visual Systems (Color, Spacing, Radius, Typography)
- Use semantic color roles (background, foreground, primary, secondary, destructive, border, etc.).
- Use the defined system scales for spacing, radius (sm, md, lg, xl), typography, and shadows.
- No arbitrary values unless explicitly justified and no semantic token exists.
- No feature-specific color palettes, spacing systems, or design systems.
- No hardcoded hex values in UI components.

---

# 2. Tailwind Usage Policy

Tailwind is a utility layer for applying styles, NOT a design system authority.

- Tailwind utilities must map to design tokens only.
- `className` must remain declarative and compositional. Use `cn()` for conditional composition.
- Avoid overly long utility chains without structure or logic-heavy styling decisions.
- Do NOT bypass the design tokens via raw/arbitrary values (e.g., `px-[13px]`) unless as an absolute exception.

---

# 3. shadcn/ui Integration Rule

shadcn/ui is a base component library (primitives layer), NOT a design system of its own.

- shadcn components must be styled ONLY via Tailwind tokens.
- No direct visual overrides outside system constraints.
- shadcn components must NOT be modified directly unless fixing a bug or aligning with token compliance.
- Use composition or wrappers instead of modifying or duplicating shadcn components.
- Use `cva` for multi-state shadcn-based components instead of ternary className logic.
- Do not create parallel versions of existing primitives.

---

# 4. Anti-Patterns

Forbidden patterns:
- Hardcoded hex colors in components.
- Inconsistent spacing, colors, radius, or elevation between features.
- Custom design systems inside features.
- One-off visual decisions not aligned with tokens.
- Uncontrolled utility proliferation or arbitrary values in Tailwind.
- Duplicating shadcn components with minor visual changes.
- Embedding feature logic into styling or primitives.
